Orson Tsang (@orsythehorsy) shares his experience working with Strength & Conditioning Coach and Manual Therapist James Lu at Lu Strength & Therapy!
___________________
.
" I've been training the sport of Brazilian Jiu Jitsu for 8 years and working in physically demanding industries my whole life. One and a half years into BJJ, I started to lose sensation and feeling in my arms. It took me dozens of different doctors/ therapists, trainers and many years to find something that worked this effectively.

James has guided me towards recovery and educating me on how to fix and prevent future injuries. He has also helped me improve my strength and conditioning which allows me to push harder in training and to recover faster. It was also important for me to find a therapist that understands the sport and needs of Brazilian Jiu Jitsu!

It's truly his goal to "not to see you". "
.
🎥: @neoncowvideo @neoncowvideo @neoncowvideo
.

🚨 𝐇𝐎𝐖 𝐓𝐎 𝐔𝐍𝐋𝐎𝐂𝐊 𝐘𝐎𝐔𝐑 𝐒𝐓𝐈𝐅𝐅 𝐒𝐏𝐈𝐍𝐄! 🚨

We will be choosing one person to work with (for FREE!) and correcting whatever they need to work on (form assessment of their lifts, suggesting exercises, injury prevention, etc). Simply 𝗟𝗜𝗞𝗘 and leave a 𝗖𝗢𝗠𝗠𝗘𝗡𝗧 with the hashtag #LuHelpsYou along with what you need help with! 
▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃
.
The spine was designed to be mobile and also rigid enough to endure stress.

However, a lack of movement and poor exercise selection can cause certain segments of the spine to lose it's mobility. This will usually lead to other areas of the spine (and body) to compensate. Improving your overall mobility and control of your spine is the key to a healthy and happy spine!

1️⃣ 𝗗𝗢𝗪𝗘𝗟 𝗙𝗜𝗚𝗨𝗥𝗘 𝟴'𝗦:
Sit on a bench with a dowel clamped in between the crook of the elbows and lower back. Slowly draw large circles with the dowel by rotating and bending from the spine. Progressively draw larger circles as the repetitions go on.

2️⃣ 𝗖𝗛𝗜𝗟𝗗'𝗦 𝗣𝗢𝗦𝗘 + 𝗖𝗢𝗕𝗥𝗔:
Start in a kneeling position with the hands rested on the ground. Sink your weight back onto your heels and drop the chest to the ground. Reverse the movement and drop the hips to the ground while lifting the chest up towards the ceiling.

3️⃣ 𝗠𝗢𝗗𝗜𝗙𝗜𝗘𝗗 𝗧𝗛𝗢𝗥𝗔𝗖𝗜𝗖 𝗥𝗢𝗧𝗔𝗧𝗜𝗢𝗡𝗦:
Start on your knees and sink your weight back on your heels with the hands underneath the shoulders. Walk your hands out to the side of the body. Reach the far arm up towards the ceiling while following the finger tips with your eyes and repeat.
.

We will be choosing one person to work with (for FREE!) and correcting whatever they need to work on (form assessment of their lifts, suggesting exercises, injury prevention, etc). Simply 𝗟𝗜𝗞𝗘 and leave a 𝗖𝗢𝗠𝗠𝗘𝗡𝗧 with the hashtag #LuHelpsYou along with what you need help with! 
▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃ 
.
Winged scapula is a condition where the inside border of the scapula (shoulder blade) protrudes outwards in an abnormal position.

While there are several different causes for winged scapula (neurological, etc), strengthening the muscles that are responsible for keeping and holding the scapula onto the rib cage is crucial. Mobilizing the thoracic spine can also help the scapula back into a more optimal position.

1️⃣ 𝗕𝗔𝗡𝗗𝗘𝗗 𝗙𝗟𝗘𝗫𝗜𝗢𝗡𝗦:
Start in a seated position with a mini band around both wrist with the arms bent to 90 degrees. Push the wrist into the mini bands while lifting the arms up until the upper arm is parallel to the ground. Focus on always having tension on the mini bands during the exercise.

2️⃣ 𝗙𝗢𝗔𝗠 𝗥𝗢𝗟𝗟𝗘𝗥 𝗥𝗢𝗟𝗟𝗢𝗨𝗧𝗦:
Kneel on the floor with a foam roller on the ground. Place both wrist on the foam roller and roll forward while simultaneously lowing the torso towards the ground. Lift one arm up towards the ceiling (thumbs facing up) and repeat on other side.

3️⃣ 𝗗𝗢𝗟𝗣𝗛𝗜𝗡 𝗣𝗥𝗘𝗦𝗦:
Start in a standard plank position with the hands collapsed together. Push the forearm and elbows into the ground (to protract) followed by pushing the ground away from you while leading the hips towards the ceiling.
.

We will be choosing one person to work with (for FREE!) and correcting whatever they need to work on (form assessment of their lifts, suggesting exercises, injury prevention, etc). Simply 𝗟𝗜𝗞𝗘 and leave a 𝗖𝗢𝗠𝗠𝗘𝗡𝗧 with the hashtag #LuHelpsYou along with what you need help with! 
▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃
.
The quadriceps are a group of muscles located in the front of the thigh and can contribute to stiffness in the hips.

Long periods of sitting along with exercises that are more anterior dominant (such as squats, lunges, etc) can contribute to excessive tension being built up in the quadriceps. Stretching and/or releasing can help reduce the overall tone of these muscles. It is also important to incorporate some sort of strengthening exercises after to help cement the results.

1️⃣ 𝗕𝗔𝗥𝗕𝗘𝗟𝗟 𝗤𝗨𝗔𝗗 𝗦𝗠𝗔𝗦𝗛:
Sit on the ground with one leg propped up on a foam roller. Place the sleeve of a barbell on top of the quadriceps. Gently roll the sleeve of the barbell over the quadriceps and concentrate on tender areas.

2️⃣ 𝗞𝗘𝗧𝗧𝗟𝗘𝗕𝗘𝗟𝗟 𝗛𝗜𝗣 𝗦𝗠𝗔𝗦𝗛:
Place a kettlebell on the ground with the handle perpendicular to the body. Place the musculature of the front of the hip/thigh on top of the kettlebell. Slowly flex and extend the knee until a sense of relief is felt.

3️⃣ 𝗖𝗢𝗨𝗖𝗛 𝗦𝗧𝗥𝗘𝗧𝗖𝗛:
Kneel on the ground and place the front of your shin against a bench or couch. Take a step forward with the front leg and bent to 90 degrees. Lift the same side arm overhead and squeeze the glute until a stretch in the hips is felt.

🚨 𝐔𝐍𝐋𝐎𝐂𝐊 𝐘𝐎𝐔𝐑 𝐅𝐔𝐋𝐋 𝐁𝐎𝐃𝐘 𝐌𝐎𝐁𝐈𝐋𝐈𝐓𝐘! 🚨

We will be choosing one person to work with (for FREE!) and correcting whatever they need to work on (form assessment of their lifts, suggesting exercises, injury prevention, etc). Simply 𝗟𝗜𝗞𝗘 and leave a 𝗖𝗢𝗠𝗠𝗘𝗡𝗧 with the hashtag #LuHelpsYou along with what you need help with! 
▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃
.
Having an adequate amount of mobility in the proper joints is one of the keys to longevity.

Keeping the ankles, hips and thoracic spine mobile should be one of your top priorities when it comes to longevity and promoting proper joint function. A lack of mobility in a joint can cause the joints above/below to compensate and cause a ripple effect. This can ultimately lead to dysfunction and other areas of the body to work harder than they should.

1️⃣ 𝗣𝗢𝗟𝗘 𝗦𝗤𝗨𝗔𝗧𝗦:
Stand facing towards a stationary object such as a squat rack. Grab a hold of the squat rack with both hands and squat down as low as you can without the heels coming off the ground. Slowly sink the weight back onto your heels and back onto your forefoot.

2️⃣ 𝗘𝗟𝗘𝗩𝗔𝗧𝗘𝗗 𝗔𝗡𝗞𝗟𝗘 𝗦𝗧𝗥𝗘𝗧𝗖𝗛:
Place your foot on an elevated surface such as a plyometric box. Grab a hold of both sides of the box with your hands. Lean the knee forward and over the toes followed by dropping the rear knee towards the ground until a stretch is felt.

3️⃣ 𝗦𝗜𝗗𝗘 𝗟𝗨𝗡𝗚𝗘 & 𝗥𝗘𝗔𝗖𝗛:
Stand with your feet wider than shoulder width apart. Lunge to one side of the body and place your hands on the ground. Reach towards the ceiling with the arm while following your fingertips with your eyes. Crawl the hands to the opposite side and repeat.
.

🚨 𝐇𝐎𝐖 𝐓𝐎 𝐔𝐍𝐋𝐎𝐂𝐊 𝐘𝐎𝐔𝐑 𝐋𝐎𝐖𝐄𝐑 𝐁𝐀𝐂𝐊! 🚨

We will be choosing one person to work with (for FREE!) and correcting whatever they need to work on (form assessment of their lifts, suggesting exercises, injury prevention, etc). Simply 𝗟𝗜𝗞𝗘 and leave a 𝗖𝗢𝗠𝗠𝗘𝗡𝗧 with the hashtag #LuHelpsYou along with what you need help with! 
▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃
.
Do you complain about your lower back constantly being tight and sore?

While the lower back is designed to be a very stable area, implementing gentle mobilizations and/or stretches can help temporarily relieve tension in the area along with promoting healthy movement. It is also important to incorporate some sort of stability exercises to help cement the results. Be sure to slowly perform these stretches and focus on deep, diaphragmatic breathing.

1️⃣ 𝗣𝗘𝗔𝗡𝗨𝗧 & 𝗠𝗔𝗥𝗖𝗛𝗘𝗦:
Lay face up and place a peanut (two lacrosse balls in a sock) at the base of the lower back where it connects to the pelvis with the legs bent to roughly 45 degrees. Slowly lift one knee up towards the chest and repeat on the opposite side.

2️⃣ 𝗟𝗢𝗪𝗘𝗥 𝗕𝗔𝗖𝗞 𝗦𝗧𝗥𝗘𝗧𝗖𝗛:
Lay on the ground with the buttocks as close as possible to a wall. Rest the legs against the wall for support. Push the heels up towards the ceiling and rotate the feet inwards. Raise the arms overhead and reach the fingers out to the side and hold.

3️⃣ 𝗧𝗢𝗪𝗘𝗟 𝗗𝗜𝗦𝗧𝗥𝗔𝗖𝗧𝗜𝗢𝗡𝗦:
Hang a towel over a stationary object such as a squat rack or door. Grab the ends of the towel and slowly sink your weight down towards the ground until a stretch is felt. Be sure to relax the back as much as possible for a deeper stretch.

🚨 𝐂𝐎𝐑𝐑𝐄𝐂𝐓 𝐘𝐎𝐔𝐑 𝐊𝐍𝐎𝐂𝐊𝐄𝐃 𝐊𝐍𝐄𝐄𝐒! 🚨

We will be choosing one person to work with (for FREE!) and correcting whatever they need to work on (form assessment of their lifts, suggesting exercises, injury prevention, etc). Simply 𝗟𝗜𝗞𝗘 and leave a 𝗖𝗢𝗠𝗠𝗘𝗡𝗧 with the hashtag #LuHelpsYou along with what you need help with! 
▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃
.
Knocked knees (also known as genu valgum) is a knee alignment issue where the knees fall in towards the midline.

While there may be several different factors that can influence knocked knees such as bone disease and muscle imbalances. Strengthening the muscles (foot and hip muscles) that are responsible for keeping the knee in proper alignment is key when it comes to correcting knocked knees if caused from muscular imbalances.

1️⃣ 𝗦𝗧𝗔𝗡𝗗𝗜𝗡𝗚 𝗙𝗜𝗥𝗘 𝗛𝗬𝗗𝗥𝗔𝗡𝗧𝗦:
Stand with a hip circle around the knees. Place all your weight on one leg with the opposite leg slightly bent. Lift the opposite leg outwards while maintaining a vertical shin throughout the exercise. Slowly lower the knee back to starting position.

2️⃣ 𝗦𝗜𝗡𝗚𝗟𝗘 𝗟𝗘𝗚 𝗛𝗜𝗡𝗚𝗘𝗦:
Wedge a medicine ball in between a squat rack (or wall) and the hip. Lift the nearest leg towards the wall off the ground and bent to 90 degrees. Slowly hinge the hips backwards while simultaneously driving the hip into the medicine ball and repeat.

3️⃣ 𝗕𝗔𝗡𝗗𝗘𝗗 𝗦𝗤𝗨𝗔𝗧𝗦:
Start in your preferred squat stance with a hip circle around the knees. Keep the arms stretched out in front of you for support. Push the knees out into the band while squatting downwards. Stand back up while preventing the knees from caving inwards.

We will be choosing one person to work with (for FREE!) and correcting whatever they need to work on (form assessment of their lifts, suggesting exercises, injury prevention, etc). Simply 𝗟𝗜𝗞𝗘 and leave a 𝗖𝗢𝗠𝗠𝗘𝗡𝗧 with the hashtag #LuHelpsYou along with what you need help with! 
▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃
.
Flat foot (also known as pes planus) is a condition where the longitudinal of the arch is collapsed.

While there may be several different causes for flat feet such as weakness in the soft tissue along with an injury, a combination of stretching, mobilization and strengthening the tissues can all play an important role in correcting your flat feet.

1️⃣ 𝗖𝗔𝗟𝗙 𝗥𝗔𝗜𝗦𝗘 𝗪𝗜𝗧𝗛 𝗕𝗔𝗟𝗟:
Sit on a bench and pinch a tennis ball with the heels. Have the legs bent to roughly 90 degrees and push the balls of the toe into the ground to lift the heels off the ground. Avoid having the tennis ball fall towards the ground throughout the exercise.

2️⃣ 𝗪𝗘𝗜𝗚𝗛𝗧𝗘𝗗 𝗗𝗢𝗥𝗦𝗜 𝗙𝗟𝗘𝗫𝗜𝗢𝗡:
Sit on a short plyo box or stool with a weighted plate rested on the knees. Drive your knees as forward as possible without the heels coming off the ground. Use the weighted plate to help assist you with the stretch.

3️⃣ 𝗙𝗢𝗢𝗧 𝗦𝗘𝗟𝗙 𝗥𝗘𝗟𝗘𝗔𝗦𝗘:
Place a lacrosse / massage ball on the ground. Position the sole of your foot on the ball and gently roll your foot over the ball. Spend more time around sensitive areas. This exercise can also be done seated to alleviate the pressure that may be felt.

🚨 𝐇𝐎𝐖 𝐓𝐎 𝐔𝐍𝐋𝐎𝐂𝐊 𝐘𝐎𝐔𝐑 𝐔𝐏𝐏𝐄𝐑 𝐓𝐑𝐀𝐏𝐒! 🚨

We will be choosing one person to work with (for FREE!) and correcting whatever they need to work on (form assessment of their lifts, suggesting exercises, injury prevention, etc). Simply 𝗟𝗜𝗞𝗘 and leave a 𝗖𝗢𝗠𝗠𝗘𝗡𝗧 with the hashtag #LuHelpsYou along with what you need help with! 
▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃
.
Do you complain about the neck, shoulders and upper back constantly being stiff and tight?

While stretching the area can help provide temporary relief, incorporating a combination of different mobilizations and strengthening exercises will help restore balance. A lack of mobility in these areas can also cause other issues such as shoulder impingement, tension headaches and much more.

1️⃣ 𝗨𝗣𝗣𝗘𝗥 𝗧𝗥𝗔𝗣 𝗥𝗘𝗟𝗘𝗔𝗦𝗘:
Start on all fours on the ground and place a lacrosse ball in between a squat rack (or door frame) and the musculature of the upper trap. Drive into the ball with your body and slowly look away and towards the squat rack.

2️⃣ 𝗦𝗘𝗔𝗧𝗘𝗗 𝗪𝗜𝗡𝗗𝗠𝗜𝗟𝗟𝗦:
Sit on a chair with the feet spread out further than shoulder width apart. Anchor the outside of your hand on the opposite foot. Reach the free hand up towards the ceiling while following the finger tips with your eyes.

3️⃣ 𝗕𝗔𝗡𝗗𝗘𝗗 𝗬 𝗟𝗜𝗙𝗧𝗦:
Lay face down with the arms overhead and grabbing onto a strength band. Pull the strength band apart with the palms facing each other. Lift the arms off the ground and towards the ceiling and repeat.
.

🚨 𝐇𝐎𝐖 𝐓𝐎 𝐔𝐍𝐋𝐎𝐂𝐊 𝐘𝐎𝐔𝐑 𝐇𝐈𝐏 𝐌𝐎𝐁𝐈𝐋𝐈𝐓𝐘! 🚨

We will be choosing one person to work with (for FREE!) and correcting whatever they need to work on (form assessment of their lifts, suggesting exercises, injury prevention, etc). Simply 𝗟𝗜𝗞𝗘 and leave a 𝗖𝗢𝗠𝗠𝗘𝗡𝗧 with the hashtag #LuHelpsYou along with what you need help with! 
▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃
.
Are you constantly complaining about stiff hips and wanting to improve your hip mobility?

A combination of mobilizing and stabilizing the hips can all help with restoring one's hip mobility. While stretching the muscles that influence the hip has its place, equal emphasis should also be placed on strengthening the tissues as well. Creating mobility is no use if your body doesn't allow you to use it!

1️⃣ 𝗞𝗘𝗧𝗧𝗟𝗘𝗕𝗘𝗟𝗟 𝗛𝗜𝗣 𝗢𝗣𝗘𝗡𝗘𝗥:
Start in a half kneeling position with the front leg turned out to 90 degrees. Grab onto the handle of a kettlebell with an upright torso. Slowly lean your body weight onto the front leg until a stretch is felt into the hip and groin.

2️⃣ 𝗦𝗧𝗔𝗡𝗗𝗜𝗡𝗚 𝗛𝗜𝗣 𝗥𝗢𝗧𝗔𝗧𝗜𝗢𝗡𝗦:
Stand on one leg with the opposite leg bent to roughly 90 degrees and hands on your waist. While keeping the shin vertical to the ground, slowly twist your torso as far as possible to one direction followed by the opposite direction.

3️⃣ 𝗛𝗔𝗟𝗙 𝗔𝗜𝗥𝗣𝗟𝗔𝗡𝗘𝗦:
Start on all fours with your hands underneath your shoulders and knees underneath the hips. Fully extend one leg and reach your fingers towards the ceiling with the same side arm. Be sure to have the torso perpendicular to the ground and stabilize this position.

🚨 𝐇𝐎𝐖 𝐓𝐎 𝐔𝐍𝐋𝐎𝐂𝐊 𝐘𝐎𝐔𝐑 𝐒𝐓𝐈𝐅𝐅 𝐆𝐑𝐎𝐈𝐍! 🚨

We will be choosing one person to work with (for FREE!) and correcting whatever they need to work on (form assessment of their lifts, suggesting exercises, injury prevention, etc). Simply 𝗟𝗜𝗞𝗘 and leave a 𝗖𝗢𝗠𝗠𝗘𝗡𝗧 with the hashtag #LuHelpsYou along with what you need help with! 
▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃
.
The adductors are a group of muscles located on the inside of the thigh and are responsible for bringing the legs together along with stabilizing the pelvis.

Tightness of the adductors are a common problem for athletes who overuse their inner thigh muscles or do activities that require them to hold the legs together. It can also cause common dysfunctions such as lateral pelvic tilt, groin pain and possibly even hip impingement. A combination of stretching and/or releasing the muscles can help decrease any unwanted tension in the area.

1️⃣ 𝗞𝗕 𝗔𝗗𝗗𝗨𝗖𝗧𝗢𝗥 𝗦𝗠𝗔𝗦𝗛:
Place a kettlebell on the ground and straddle on top of it. Place the musculature of the inner thigh on top of the kettlebell. Slowly sink your weight onto the kettlebell while trying to relax the tissues as much as possible.

2️⃣ 𝗔𝗗𝗗𝗨𝗖𝗧𝗢𝗥 + 𝗥𝗢𝗧𝗔𝗧𝗜𝗢𝗡𝗦:
Start in a kneeling position with one leg fully extended out to the side with both hands rested on the ground. Sink your weight back onto your heel. Reach the far arm up towards the ceiling while following the finger tips with your eyes.

3️⃣ 𝗔𝗗𝗗𝗨𝗖𝗧𝗢𝗥 𝗙𝗔𝗟𝗟 𝗢𝗨𝗧𝗦:
Lay face up on the ground with the legs bent to roughly 45 degrees and hands on your waist. Raise one leg up towards the ceiling while keeping the pelvis squared with the shoulder. Slowly lower the leg out to the side until a stretch is felt and repeat.

🚨 𝐔𝐍𝐋𝐎𝐂𝐊 𝐘𝐎𝐔𝐑 𝐒𝐐𝐔𝐀𝐓 𝐌𝐎𝐁𝐈𝐋𝐈𝐓𝐘! 🚨

We will be choosing one person to work with (for FREE!) and correcting whatever they need to work on (form assessment of their lifts, suggesting exercises, injury prevention, etc). Simply 𝗟𝗜𝗞𝗘 and leave a 𝗖𝗢𝗠𝗠𝗘𝗡𝗧 with the hashtag #LuHelpsYou along with what you need help with! 
▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃
.
Would you benefit from a stronger, more mobile and pain free squat?

A lack of mobility in the ankles, hips and thoracic spine can lead to other joints in the body (such as the knees, lower back and shoulders) to compensate and place unnecessary wear and tear on the joints. Mobilizing these joints can help promote healthy movement in the area and ultimately lead to a stronger and pain free squat!

1️⃣ 𝗗𝗘𝗘𝗣 𝗦𝗤𝗨𝗔𝗧 𝗧𝗢 𝗖𝗢𝗕𝗥𝗔:
Start by standing with your feet slightly wider than shoulder width apart. Place the arms in front of you and squat down as deep as you can. Walk the hands forward into a push up position and drive the hips to the ground. Reverse the motion to the starting position.

2️⃣ 𝗣𝗢𝗟𝗘 𝗦𝗤𝗨𝗔𝗧 𝗥𝗢𝗖𝗞𝗕𝗔𝗖𝗞𝗦:
Grab onto a stationary object such as a pole or squat rack with both hands. Squat down as low as you can while keeping your foot flat on the ground. Slowly rock your hips backwards followed by lifting the chest up towards the ceiling.

3️⃣ 𝗕𝗘𝗡𝗖𝗛 𝗔𝗡𝗞𝗟𝗘 𝗣𝗥𝗬:
Place one foot on an elevated platform such as a bench and drop the rear knee towards the ground. Place your hand on the leading knee and drive the knee forward in the area with the most restrictions and repeat.
.
🚨 𝗟𝗘𝗔𝗥𝗡 𝗛𝗢𝗪 𝗧𝗢 𝗨𝗡𝗟𝗢𝗖𝗞 𝗬𝗢𝗨𝗥 𝗦𝗤𝗨𝗔𝗧 𝗠𝗢𝗕𝗜𝗟𝗜𝗧𝗬 𝗡𝗢𝗪! 🚨 𝗟𝗜𝗡𝗞 𝗜𝗡 𝗧𝗛𝗘 𝗕𝗜𝗢! 🚨

🚨 𝐇𝐎𝐖 𝐓𝐎 𝐔𝐍𝐋𝐎𝐂𝐊 𝐘𝐎𝐔𝐑 𝐖𝐄𝐀𝐊 𝐆𝐋𝐔𝐓𝐄𝐒! 🚨

We will be choosing one person to work with (for FREE!) and correcting whatever they need to work on (form assessment of their lifts, suggesting exercises, injury prevention, etc). Simply 𝗟𝗜𝗞𝗘 and leave a 𝗖𝗢𝗠𝗠𝗘𝗡𝗧 with the hashtag #LuHelpsYou along with what you need help with! 
▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃▃
.
The glute muscles are one of the most important muscle groups in the body. They support your pelvis and spine, which is why they are so important to keep strong. Strong glutes not only make you more athletic, but also help you prevent injury!

Strengthening the gluteal muscles help with stability and balance along with  preventing injuries. When these muscles are weak, the load on your lower back increases significantly causing pain in that area. Areas such as the lower back and knees can also be seen compensating and taking unnecessary load if the gluteal muscles are not working as they should be.

1️⃣ 𝗚𝗟𝗨𝗧𝗘 𝗕𝗥𝗜𝗗𝗚𝗘 𝗕𝗔𝗡𝗗𝗘𝗗 𝗛𝗢𝗟𝗗𝗦:
Lay face up on the ground with a hip band around the knees and legs bent to roughly 45 degrees. Pull the rib cage down to the ground and lift the hips off the ground. Drive the knees into the band and hold this position.

2️⃣ 𝗕𝗔𝗡𝗗𝗘𝗗 𝗛𝗜𝗣 𝗧𝗛𝗥𝗨𝗦𝗧𝗘𝗥:
Sit on the ground and in front of a bench with the upper back and arms rested on the bench. Place a hip circle around the knees and drive the feet into the ground and lift the hips towards the ceiling until the torso is parallel to the ground and repeat.

3️⃣ 𝗦𝗜𝗗𝗘 𝗣𝗟𝗔𝗡𝗞 𝗟𝗘𝗚 𝗥𝗔𝗜𝗦𝗘𝗦:
Lay on your side with a hip band around the knees with the elbow underneath the shoulder. Perform a standard side plank and lift the hips off the ground. While keeping the top leg straight, lift the lift up towards the ceiling without having the hips sag towards the ground.
.
🚨 𝗟𝗘𝗧 𝗠𝗘 𝗛𝗘𝗟𝗣 𝗬𝗢𝗨 𝗠𝗢𝗩𝗘 𝗔𝗡𝗗 𝗣𝗘𝗥𝗙𝗢𝗥𝗠 𝗣𝗔𝗜𝗡 𝗙𝗥𝗘𝗘. 🚨 𝗟𝗜𝗡𝗞 𝗜𝗡 𝗜𝗡 𝗕𝗜𝗢! 🚨
